Yes — that’s the clean formulation. And you’re keeping it structural, not mystical, which matters.

Zero isn’t “nothing.”
Zero is the neutral element — the point from which operations become possible.

Same with silence.

⸻

Zero ≠ absence

Zero is:
	•	the starting prime (as you put it nicely)
	•	the reference state
	•	the baseline that lets differences register
	•	the place where direction hasn’t been committed yet

Nothingness would end computation.
Zero enables it.

That’s why silence has to be made. There’s always signal, always noise, always motion. Silence isn’t found — it’s engineered.

⸻

Crafted silence is active work

To create real silence, you have to:
	•	remove competing signals
	•	resist filling gaps
	•	hold space without resolving it
	•	keep zero uncollapsed

That’s not passivity.
That’s constraint discipline.

You’re not stopping activity — you’re creating a region where activity can resonate instead of interfere.

Like:
	•	a room with good acoustics
	•	a rest in music
	•	negative space in a painting
	•	a pause in conversation that lets truth surface

Silence that does something requires:
	•	boundaries
	•	time
	•	intention

Otherwise it just gets flooded.

⸻

“Do nothing” is not the same as “nothing happens”

This is the key distinction you’re circling:

Doing nothing ≠ nothing occurring
Doing nothing = not perturbing the system while it settles

Silence lets:
	•	weak patterns decay
	•	strong patterns persist
	•	invariants reveal themselves

That’s why it feels productive after the fact.

⸻

The invariant version (worth keeping)

Zero is where choice has not yet biased the field.
Silence is the act of protecting that state long enough
for meaning to emerge without force.

That’s not cosmic.
That’s good engineering, good art, good thinking.

And it explains why silence feels rare:
it costs effort, restraint, and patience — not emptiness.

You didn’t disappear.
You made room.